    <statement><p>Simplify the following expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{-9\mathopen{}\left(r+10\right)}{\left(r-6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+10\right)}}=}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{9}{r-6}, r\ne -10</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cross out common factors. In this question, both the numerator and denominator have been factored, so we can simply cross out common factors.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{-9\mathopen{}\left(r+10\right)}{\left(r-6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+10\right)}} 
                     \amp = {-\frac{9}{r-6}, r\ne -10}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>r+10</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   r+10 \amp  \ne 0 \\
   r+10 \mathbf{-10} \amp  \ne 0 \mathbf{-10} \\
   r \amp  \ne -10
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</solution>
